[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The deepfakes of Kim and Putin were meant to air publicly as commercials to relay the notion that interference by these leaders in US elections would be detrimental to the United States' democracy.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The commercials also aimed to shock Americans to realize how fragile democracy is, and how media and news can significantly influence the country's path regardless of credibility.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] However, while the commercials included an ending comment detailing that the footage was not real, they ultimately did not air due to fears and sensitivity regarding how Americans may react.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] On 5 June 2023, an unknown source broadcast a reported deepfake of Vladimir Putin on multiple radio and television networks.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In the clip, Putin appears to deliver a speech announcing the invasion of Russia and calling for a general mobilization of the army.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Russian social media boosted it, but after it was debunked, Facebook and YouTube removed it.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Twitter allowed the video in tweets where it was exposed as a fake, but said it would be taken down if posted to deceive people.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] It was not immediately clear who created the deepfake, to which Zelenskyy responded with his own video, saying, "We don't plan to lay down any arms.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In late 2022, pro-China propagandists started spreading deepfake videos purporting to be from "Wolf News" that used synthetic actors.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The technology was developed by a London company called Synthesia, which markets it as a cheap alternative to live actors for training and HR videos.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The image went viral, receiving over twenty million views.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] dubbed it "the first real mass-level AI misinformation case".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] characterized the image as unsophisticated: "you could have made it on Photoshop five years ago".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Party leader Keir Starmer abusing staffers was released on the first day of a Labour Party conference.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The clip purported to be an audio tape of Starmer abusing his staffers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] fell prey to DeepFake when a morphed video of a famous British-Indian influencer, Zara Patel, with Rashmika's face started to float on social media.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Zara Patel claims to not be involved in its creation.
