[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Dela Rosa lauded the supposed youth for their opinions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] When informed it was an AI video, he says that if that was the case the video creator had a point.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Duterte herself defended Dela Rosa, insisting that sharing an AI video is not wrong as long as its "not for profit".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] condemned an AI-generated deepfake video that mimicked an RTÉ News report and falsely claimed she was withdrawing from the presidential election; her campaign reported the video to the social media platforms it appeared on.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Chat site Discord took action against deepfake pornography in 2018, and has taken a general stance against deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Gfycat began removing all deepfakes from its site on 31 January 2018.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Reddit banned the r/deepfakes subreddit on 7 February 2018, due to the policy violation of "involuntary pornography".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Also in February 2018, Pornhub said that it would ban deepfake videos on its website because it is considered "non consensual content" which violates their terms of service.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] They had also stated previously that they will take down content flagged as deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Writers from *Motherboard* reported that searching "deepfakes" on Pornhub still returned multiple recent deepfake videos.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Google added "involuntary synthetic pornographic imagery" to its ban list in September 2018, allowing anyone to request the block of results showing their fake nudes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In May 2022, Google officially changed the terms of service for their Jupyter Notebook colabs, banning the use of their colab service for the purpose of creating deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Facebook has previously stated that they would not remove deepfakes from their platforms.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The videos will instead be flagged as fake by third-parties and then have a lessened priority in user's feeds.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] This response was prompted in June 2019 after a deepfake featuring a 2016 video of Mark Zuckerberg circulated on Facebook and Instagram.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Subsequently, Facebook has taken efforts towards encouraging the creation of deepfakes in order to develop state of the art deepfake detection software.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Facebook was the prominent partner in hosting the Deepfake Detection Challenge (DFDC), held December 2019, to 2114 participants who generated more than 35,000 models.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The top performing models with the highest detection accuracy were analyzed for similarities and differences; these findings are areas of interest in further research to improve and refine deepfake detection models.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Facebook has also detailed that the platform will be taking down media generated with artificial intelligence used to alter an individual's speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] However, media that has been edited to alter the order or context of words in one's message would remain on the site but be labeled as false, since it was not generated by artificial intelligence.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In February 2018, representatives from Twitter (now X) stated that they would suspend accounts suspected of posting non-consensual deepfake content.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In 2019, Twitter announced it was seeking public feedback on a prospective policy for its handling of "synthetic and manipulated media".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Under the draft policy, *TechCrunch* reported that Twitter "would label and warn, but not always remove, manipulated media".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In the United States, there have been some responses to the problems posed by deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In 2018, the Malicious Deep Fake Prohibition Act was introduced to the US Senate; in 2019, the Deepfakes Accountability Act was introduced in the 116th United States Congress by U.S. representative for New York's 9th congressional district Yvette Clarke.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Among U.S. legislative efforts, on 3 October 2019, California governor Gavin Newsom signed into law Assembly Bills No.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] 602 provides individuals targeted by sexually explicit deepfake content made without their consent with a cause of action against the content's creator.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] 730 prohibits the distribution of malicious deepfake audio or visual media targeting a candidate running for public office within 60 days of their election.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] U.S. representative Yvette Clarke introduced H.R.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] 5586: Deepfakes Accountability Act into the 118th United States Congress on 20 September 2023 in an effort to protect national security from threats posed by deepfake technology.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] U.S. representative María Salazar introduced H.R.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] 6943: No AI Fraud Act into the 118th United States Congress on 10 January 2024, to establish specific property rights of individual physicality, including voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In 2016, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) launched the Media Forensics (MediFor) program which was funded through 2020.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] MediFor aimed at automatically spotting digital manipulation in images and videos, including Deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In the summer of 2018, MediFor held an event where individuals competed to create AI-generated videos, audio, and images as well as automated tools to detect these deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] According to the MediFor program, it established a framework of three tiers of information—digital integrity, physical integrity and semantic integrity—to generate one integrity score in an effort to enable accurate detection of manipulated media.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In 2019, DARPA hosted a "proposers day" for the Semantic Forensics (SemaFor) program where researchers were driven to prevent viral spread of AI-manipulated media.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] DARPA and the Semantic Forensics Program were also working together to detect AI-manipulated media through efforts in training computers to utilize common sense, logical reasoning.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] Built on the MediFor's technologies, SemaFor's attribution algorithms infer if digital media originates from a particular organization or individual, while characterization algorithms determine whether media was generated or manipulated for malicious purposes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] In March 2024, SemaFor published an analytic catalog that offers the public access to open-source resources developed under SemaFor.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/deepfake-p02] The International Panel on the Information Environment was launched in 2023 as a consortium of over 250 scientists working to develop effective countermeasures to deepfakes and other problems created by perverse incentives in organizations disseminating information via the Internet.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In speech science and phonetics, a **formant** is the broad spectral maximum that results from an acoustic resonance of the human vocal tract.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In acoustics, a formant is usually defined as a broad peak, or local maximum, in the spectrum.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] For harmonic sounds, with this definition, the formant frequency is sometimes taken as that of the harmonic that is most augmented by a resonance.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The difference between these two definitions resides in whether "formants" characterise the production mechanisms of a sound or the produced sound itself.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In practice, the frequency of a spectral peak differs slightly from the associated resonance frequency, except when, by luck, harmonics are aligned with the resonance frequency, or when the sound source is mostly non-harmonic, as in whispering and vocal fry.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] A room can be said to have formants characteristic of that particular room, due to its resonances, i.e., to the way sound reflects from its walls and objects.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Room formants of this nature reinforce themselves by emphasizing specific frequencies and absorbing others, as exploited, for example, by Alvin Lucier in his piece *I Am Sitting in a Room*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In acoustic digital signal processing, the way a collection of formants (such as a room) affects a signal can be represented by an impulse response.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In both speech and rooms, formants are characteristic features of the resonances of the space.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] They are said to be *excited* by acoustic sources such as the voice, and they shape (filter) the sources' sounds, but they are not sources themselves.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] From an acoustic point of view, phonetics had a serious problem with the idea that the effective length of vocal tract changed vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Indeed, when the length of the vocal tract changes, all the acoustic resonators formed by mouth cavities are scaled, and so are their resonance frequencies.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Therefore, it was unclear how vowels could depend on frequencies when talkers with different vocal tract lengths, for instance bass and soprano singers, can produce sounds that are perceived as belonging to the same phonetic category.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] There had to be some way to normalize the spectral information underpinning the vowel identity.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Hermann suggested a solution to this problem in 1894, coining the term “formant”.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] A vowel, according to him, is a special acoustic phenomenon, depending on the intermittent production of a special partial, or “formant”, or “characteristique” feature.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The frequency of the “formant” may vary a little without altering the character of the vowel.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] For “long e” (*ee* or *iy*) for example, the lowest-frequency “formant” may vary from 350 to 440 Hz even in the same person.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Formants are distinctive frequency components of the acoustic signal produced by speech, musical instruments or singing.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The information that humans require to distinguish between speech sounds can be represented purely quantitatively by specifying peaks in the frequency spectrum.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Most of these formants are produced by tube and chamber resonance, but a few whistle tones derive from periodic collapse of Venturi effect low-pressure zones.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The formant with the lowest frequency is called *F*1, the second *F*2, the third *F*3, and so forth.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The fundamental frequency or pitch of the voice is sometimes referred to as *F*0, but it is not a formant.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Most often the two first formants, *F*1 and *F*2, are sufficient to identify the vowel.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The relationship between the perceived vowel quality and the first two formant frequencies can be appreciated by listening to "artificial vowels" that are generated by passing a click train (to simulate the glottal pulse train) through a pair of bandpass filters (to simulate vocal tract resonances).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Front vowels have higher *F*2, while low vowels have higher *F*1.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Lip rounding tends to lower *F*1 and *F*2 in back vowels and *F*2 and *F*3 in front vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Lowering of *F*3 is also a primary characteristic of r-colored vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Nasal consonants usually have an additional formant around 2500 Hz.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The liquid [l] usually has an extra formant at 1500 Hz, whereas the English "r" sound ([ɹ]) is distinguished by a very low third formant (well below 2000 Hz).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Plosives (and, to some degree, fricatives) modify the placement of formants in the surrounding vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The time course of these changes in vowel formant frequencies are referred to as 'formant transitions'.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In normal voiced speech, the underlying vibration produced by the vocal folds resembles a sawtooth wave, rich in harmonic overtones.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] If the fundamental frequency or (more often) one of the overtones is higher than a resonance frequency of the system, then the resonance will be only weakly excited and the formant usually imparted by that resonance will be mostly lost.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] This is most apparent in the case of soprano opera singers, who sing at pitches high enough that their vowels become very hard to distinguish.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Control of resonances is an essential component of the vocal technique known as overtone singing, in which the performer sings a low fundamental tone, and creates sharp resonances to select upper harmonics, giving the impression of several tones being sung at once.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Spectrograms may be used to visualise formants.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In spectrograms, it can be hard to distinguish formants from naturally occurring harmonics when one sings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] However, one can hear the natural formants in a vowel shape through atonal techniques such as vocal fry.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Formants, whether they are seen as acoustic resonances of the vocal tract, or as local maxima in the speech spectrum, like band-pass filters, are defined by their frequency and by their spectral width (bandwidth).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Different methods exist to obtain this information.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Formant frequencies, in their acoustic definition, can be estimated from the frequency spectrum of the sound, using a spectrogram (in the figure) or a spectrum analyzer.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] However, to estimate the acoustic resonances of the vocal tract (i.e. the speech definition of formants) from a speech recording, one can use *linear predictive coding*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] An intermediate approach consists in extracting the spectral envelope by neutralizing the fundamental frequency, and only then looking for local maxima in the spectral envelope.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The first two formants are important in determining the quality of vowels, and are frequently said to correspond to the open–close (or low–high) and front–back dimensions (which have traditionally been associated with the shape and position of the tongue).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Thus the first formant *F*1 has a higher frequency for an open or low vowel such as [a] and a lower frequency for a closed or high vowel such as [i] or [u]; and the second formant *F*2 has a higher frequency for a front vowel such as [i] and a lower frequency for a back vowel such as [u].
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Vowels will almost always have four or more distinguishable formants, and sometimes more than six.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] However, the first two formants are the most important in determining vowel quality and are often plotted against each other in vowel diagrams, though this simplification fails to capture some aspects of vowel quality such as rounding.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Many writers have addressed the problem of finding an optimal alignment of the positions of vowels on formant plots with those on the conventional vowel quadrilateral.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] The pioneering work of Ladefoged used the Mel scale because this scale was claimed to correspond more closely to the auditory scale of pitch than to the acoustic measure of fundamental frequency expressed in Hertz.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Two alternatives to the Mel scale are the Bark scale and the ERB-rate scale.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Another widely adopted strategy is plotting the difference between *F*1 and *F*2 rather than *F*2 on the horizontal axis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] Studies of the frequency spectrum of trained speakers and classical singers, especially male singers, indicate a clear formant around 3000 Hz (between 2800 and 3400 Hz) that is absent in speech or in the spectra of untrained speakers or singers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] It is thought to be associated with one or more of the higher resonances of the vocal tract.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] It is this increase in energy at 3000 Hz which allows singers to be heard and understood over an orchestra.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] This formant is actively developed through vocal training, for instance through so-called *voce di strega* or "witch's voice" exercises and is caused by a part of the vocal tract acting as a resonator.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/formant] In classical music and vocal pedagogy, this phenomenon is also known as *squillo*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Early attempts at speech processing and recognition were primarily focused on understanding a handful of simple phonetic elements such as vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In 1952, three researchers at Bell Labs, Stephen.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Davis, developed a system that could recognize digits spoken by a single speaker.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Pioneering works in field of speech recognition using analysis of its spectrum were reported in the 1940s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Linear predictive coding (LPC), a speech processing algorithm, was first proposed by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Further developments in LPC technology were made by Bishnu S.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Schroeder at Bell Labs during the 1970s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] LPC was the basis for voice-over-IP (VoIP) technology, as well as speech synthesizer chips, such as the Texas Instruments LPC Speech Chips used in the Speak & Spell toys from 1978.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] One of the first commercially available speech recognition products was Dragon Dictate, released in 1990.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In 1992, technology developed by Lawrence Rabiner and others at Bell Labs was used by AT&T in their Voice Recognition Call Processing service to route calls without a human operator.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] By this point, the vocabulary of these systems was larger than the average human vocabulary.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] By the early 2000s, the dominant speech processing strategy started to shift away from Hidden Markov Models towards more modern neural networks and deep learning.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In 2012, Geoffrey Hinton and his team at the University of Toronto demonstrated that deep neural networks could significantly outperform traditional HMM-based systems on large vocabulary continuous speech recognition tasks.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] This breakthrough led to widespread adoption of deep learning techniques in the industry.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] By the mid-2010s, companies like Google, Microsoft, Amazon, and Apple had integrated advanced speech recognition systems into their virtual assistants such as Google Assistant, Cortana, Alexa, and Siri.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] These systems utilized deep learning models to provide more natural and accurate voice interactions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] The development of Transformer-based models, like Google's BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) and OpenAI's GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer), further pushed the boundaries of natural language processing and speech recognition.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] These models enabled more context-aware and semantically rich understanding of speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In recent years, end-to-end speech recognition models have gained popularity.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] These models simplify the speech recognition pipeline by directly converting audio input into text output, bypassing intermediate steps like feature extraction and acoustic modeling.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] This approach has streamlined the development process and improved performance.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Dynamic time warping (DTW) is an algorithm for measuring similarity between two temporal sequences, which may vary in speed.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In general, DTW is a method that calculates an optimal match between two given sequences (e.g. time series) with certain restrictions and rules.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] The optimal match is denoted by the match that satisfies all the restrictions and the rules and that has the minimal cost, where the cost is computed as the sum of absolute differences for each matched pair of indices between their values.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] A hidden Markov model can be represented as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] The goal of the algorithm is to estimate a hidden variable x(t) given a list of observations y(t).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] By applying the Markov property, the conditional probability distribution of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) at time *t*, given the values of the hidden variable *x* at all times, depends *only* on the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t* − 1).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Similarly, the value of the observed variable *y*(*t*) only depends on the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) (both at time *t*).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] An artificial neural network (ANN) is based on a collection of connected units or nodes called artificial neurons, which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit a signal from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Phase is often assumed to be random, but contains useful information.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Wrapping of phase: can be introduced due to periodical jumps on $2\pi$ .
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Obtained phase estimations can be used for noise reduction: temporal smoothing of instantaneous phase and its derivatives by time (instantaneous frequency) and frequency (group delay), smoothing of phase across frequency.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-processing] Joined amplitude and phase estimators can recover speech more accurately based on the assumption of a von Mises distribution of phase.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Synthesized speech can be created by concatenating pieces of recorded speech that are stored in a database.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Systems differ in the size of the stored speech units; a system that stores phones or diphones provides the largest output range, but may lack clarity.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For specific usage domains, the storage of entire words or sentences allows for high-quality output.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Alternatively, a synthesizer can incorporate a model of the vocal tract and other human voice characteristics to create a completely "synthetic" voice output.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The quality of a speech synthesizer is judged by its similarity to the human voice and by its ability to be understood clearly.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] An intelligible text-to-speech program allows people with visual impairments or reading disabilities to listen to written words on a home computer.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The earliest computer operating system to have included a speech synthesizer was Unix in 1974, through the Unix speak utility.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 2000, Microsoft Sam was the default text-to-speech voice synthesizer used by the narrator accessibility feature, which shipped with all Windows 2000 operating systems, and subsequent Windows XP systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A text-to-speech system (or "engine") is composed of two parts: a front-end and a back-end.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] First, it converts raw text containing symbols like numbers and abbreviations into the equivalent of written-out words.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This process is often called *text normalization*, *pre-processing*, or *tokenization*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The front-end then assigns phonetic transcriptions to each word, and divides and marks the text into prosodic units, like phrases, clauses, and sentences.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The process of assigning phonetic transcriptions to words is called *text-to-phoneme* or *grapheme-to-phoneme* conversion.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Phonetic transcriptions and prosody information together make up the symbolic linguistic representation that is output by the front-end.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The back-end—often referred to as the *synthesizer*—then converts the symbolic linguistic representation into sound.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In certain systems, this part includes the computation of the *target prosody* (pitch contour, phoneme durations), which is then imposed on the output speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Long before the invention of electronic signal processing, some people tried to build machines to emulate human speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] There were also legends of the existence of "Brazen Heads", such as those involving Pope Silvester II (d.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] There followed the bellows-operated "acoustic-mechanical speech machine" of Wolfgang von Kempelen of Pressburg, Hungary, described in a 1791 paper.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This machine added models of the tongue and lips, enabling it to produce consonants as well as vowels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1837, Charles Wheatstone produced a "speaking machine" based on von Kempelen's design, and in 1846, Joseph Faber exhibited the "Euphonia".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1923, Paget resurrected Wheatstone's design.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In the 1930s, Bell Labs developed the vocoder, which automatically analyzed speech into its fundamental tones and resonances.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] From his work on the vocoder, Homer Dudley developed a keyboard-operated voice-synthesizer called The Voder (Voice Demonstrator), which he exhibited at the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Cooper and his colleagues at Haskins Laboratories built the pattern playback in the late 1940s and completed it in 1950.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] There were several different versions of this hardware device; only one currently survives.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The machine converts pictures of the acoustic patterns of speech in the form of a spectrogram back into sound.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Using this device, Alvin Liberman and colleagues discovered acoustic cues for the perception of phonetic segments (consonants and vowels).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The first computer-based speech-synthesis systems originated in the late 1950s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Noriko Umeda *et al.* developed the first general English text-to-speech system in 1968, at the Electrotechnical Laboratory in Japan.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1961, physicist John Larry Kelly, Jr and his colleague Louis Gerstman used an IBM 7090 computer to synthesize speech, an event among the most prominent in the history of Bell Labs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Kelly's voice recorder synthesizer (vocoder) recreated the song "Daisy Bell", with musical accompaniment from Max Mathews.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Clarke was visiting his friend and colleague John Pierce at the Bell Labs Murray Hill facility.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Clarke was so impressed by the demonstration that he used it in the climactic scene of his screenplay for his novel *2001: A Space Odyssey*, where the HAL 9000 computer sings the same song as astronaut Dave Bowman puts it to sleep.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Despite the success of purely electronic speech synthesis, research into mechanical speech-synthesizers continues.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Linear predictive coding (LPC), a form of speech coding, began development with the work of Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] LPC was later the basis for early speech synthesizer chips, such as the Texas Instruments LPC Speech Chips used in the Speak & Spell toys from 1978.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1975, Fumitada Itakura developed the line spectral pairs (LSP) method for high-compression speech coding, while at NTT.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] From 1975 to 1981, Itakura studied problems in speech analysis and synthesis based on the LSP method.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1980, his team developed an LSP-based speech synthesizer chip.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] LSP is an important technology for speech synthesis and coding, and in the 1990s was adopted by almost all international speech coding standards as an essential component, contributing to the enhancement of digital speech communication over mobile channels and the internet.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1975, MUSA was released, and was one of the first Speech Synthesis systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It consisted of a stand-alone computer hardware and a specialized software that enabled it to read Italian.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A second version, released in 1978, was also able to sing Italian in an "a cappella" style.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Dominant systems in the 1980s and 1990s were the DECtalk system, based largely on the work of Dennis Klatt at MIT, and the Bell Labs system; the latter was one of the first multilingual language-independent systems, making extensive use of natural language processing methods.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Handheld electronics featuring speech synthesis began emerging in the 1970s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] One of the first was the Telesensory Systems Inc.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] (TSI) *Speech+* portable calculator for the blind in 1976.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Other devices had primarily educational purposes, such as the Speak & Spell toy produced by Texas Instruments in 1978.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Fidelity released a speaking version of its electronic chess computer in 1979.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The first video game to feature speech synthesis was the 1980 shoot 'em up arcade game, *Stratovox* (known in Japan as *Speak & Rescue*), from Sun Electronics.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The first personal computer game with speech synthesis was *Manbiki Shoujo* (*Shoplifting Girl*), released in 1980 for the PET 2001, for which the game's developer, Hiroshi Suzuki, developed a "*zero cross*" programming technique to produce a synthesized speech waveform.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Another early example, the arcade version of *Berzerk*, also dates from 1980.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Milton Bradley Company produced the first multi-player electronic game using voice synthesis, *Milton*, in the same year.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 1976, Computalker Consultants released their CT-1 Speech Synthesizer.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Lloyd Rice and Jim Cooper, it was an analog synthesizer built to work with microcomputers using the S-100 bus standard.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Synthesized voices typically sounded male until 1990, when Ann Syrdal, at AT&T Bell Laboratories, created a female voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Ray Kurzweil predicted in 2005 that as the cost-performance ratio caused speech synthesizers to become cheaper and more accessible, more people would benefit from the use of text-to-speech programs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In September 2016, DeepMind released WaveNet, which demonstrated that deep learning models are capable of modeling raw waveforms and generating speech from acoustic features like spectrograms or mel-spectrograms, starting the field of deep learning speech synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Although WaveNet was initially considered to be computationally expensive and slow to be used in consumer products at the time, a year after its release, DeepMind unveiled a modified version of WaveNet known as "Parallel WaveNet," a production model 1,000 times faster than the original.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This was followed by Google AI's Tacotron 2 in 2018, which demonstrated that neural networks could produce highly natural speech synthesis but required substantial training data—typically tens of hours of audio—to achieve acceptable quality.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Tacotron 2 employed an autoencoder architecture with attention mechanisms to convert input text into mel-spectrograms, which were then converted to waveforms using a separate neural vocoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] When trained on smaller datasets, such as 2 hours of speech, the output quality degraded while still being able to maintain intelligible speech, and with just 24 minutes of training data, Tacotron 2 failed to produce intelligible speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 2019, Microsoft Research introduced FastSpeech, which addressed speed limitations in autoregressive models like Tacotron 2.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The same year saw the release of HiFi-GAN, a generative adversarial network (GAN)-based vocoder that improved the efficiency of waveform generation while producing high-fidelity speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 2020, the release of Glow-TTS introduced a flow-based approach that allowed for both fast inference and voice style transfer capabilities.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In March 2020, the free text-to-speech website 15.ai was launched.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] 15.ai gained widespread international attention in early 2021 for its ability to synthesize emotionally expressive speech of fictional characters from popular media with minimal amount of data.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The creator of 15.ai stated that 15 seconds of training data is sufficient to perfectly clone a person's voice (hence its name, "15.ai"), a significant reduction from the previously known data requirement of tens of hours.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] 15.ai is credited as the first platform to popularize AI voice cloning in memes and content creation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In January 2022, the first instance of speech synthesis NFT fraud occurred when a cryptocurrency company called Voiceverse generated voice lines using 15.ai, pitched them up to sound unrecognizable, promoted them as the byproduct of their own technology, and sold them as NFTs without permission.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In January 2023, ElevenLabs launched its browser-based text-to-speech platform, which employs advanced algorithms to analyze contextual aspects of text and detect emotions such as anger, sadness, happiness, or alarm.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The platform is able to adjust intonation and pacing based on linguistic context to produce lifelike speech with human-like inflection, and offers features including multilingual speech generation and long-form content creation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In March 2024, OpenAI corroborated the 15 second benchmark to clone a human's voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, they deemed their Voice Engine tool "too risky" for general release, stating that they would only release a preview and not release the technology for public use.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The most important qualities of a speech synthesis system are *naturalness* and *intelligibility*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Naturalness describes how closely the output sounds like human speech, while intelligibility is the ease with which the output is understood.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The ideal speech synthesizer is both natural and intelligible.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems usually try to maximize both characteristics.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The two primary technologies generating synthetic speech waveforms are *concatenative synthesis* and *formant synthesis*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Each technology has strengths and weaknesses, and the intended uses of a synthesis system will typically determine which approach is used.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Concatenative synthesis is based on the concatenation (stringing together) of segments of recorded speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Generally, concatenative synthesis produces the most natural-sounding synthesized speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, differences between natural variations in speech and the nature of the automated techniques for segmenting the waveforms sometimes result in audible glitches in the output.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] There are three main sub-types of concatenative synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Unit selection synthesis uses large databases of recorded speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] During database creation, each recorded utterance is segmented into some or all of the following: individual phones, diphones, half-phones, syllables, morphemes, words, phrases, and sentences.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Typically, the division into segments is done using a specially modified speech recognizer set to a "forced alignment" mode with some manual correction afterward, using visual representations such as the waveform and spectrogram.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] An index of the units in the speech database is then created based on the segmentation and acoustic parameters like the fundamental frequency (pitch), duration, position in the syllable, and neighboring phones.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] At run time, the desired target utterance is created by determining the best chain of candidate units from the database (unit selection).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This process is typically achieved using a specially weighted decision tree.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Unit selection provides the greatest naturalness, because it applies only a small amount of digital signal processing (DSP) to the recorded speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] DSP often makes recorded speech sound less natural, although some systems use a small amount of signal processing at the point of concatenation to smooth the waveform.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The output from the best unit-selection systems is often indistinguishable from real human voices, especially in contexts for which the TTS system has been tuned.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, maximum naturalness typically require unit-selection speech databases to be very large, in some systems ranging into the gigabytes of recorded data, representing dozens of hours of speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Also, unit selection algorithms have been known to select segments from a place that results in less than ideal synthesis (e.g. minor words become unclear) even when a better choice exists in the database.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Recently, researchers have proposed various automated methods to detect unnatural segments in unit-selection speech synthesis systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Diphone synthesis uses a minimal speech database containing all the diphones (sound-to-sound transitions) occurring in a language.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The number of diphones depends on the phonotactics of the language: for example, Spanish has about 800 diphones, and German about 2500.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In diphone synthesis, only one example of each diphone is contained in the speech database.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] At runtime, the target prosody of a sentence is superimposed on these minimal units by means of digital signal processing techniques such as linear predictive coding, PSOLA or MBROLA. or more recent techniques such as pitch modification in the source domain using discrete cosine transform.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Diphone synthesis suffers from the sonic glitches of concatenative synthesis and the robotic-sounding nature of formant synthesis, and has few of the advantages of either approach other than small size.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] As such, its use in commercial applications is declining, although it continues to be used in research because there are a number of freely available software implementations.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] An early example of Diphone synthesis is a teaching robot, Leachim, that was invented by Michael J.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Leachim contained information regarding class curricular and certain biographical information about the students whom it was programmed to teach.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It was tested in a fourth grade classroom in the Bronx, New York.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Domain-specific synthesis concatenates prerecorded words and phrases to create complete utterances.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It is used in applications where the variety of texts the system will output is limited to a particular domain, like transit schedule announcements or weather reports.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The technology is very simple to implement, and has been in commercial use for a long time, in devices like talking clocks and calculators.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The level of naturalness of these systems can be very high because the variety of sentence types is limited, and they closely match the prosody and intonation of the original recordings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Because these systems are limited by the words and phrases in their databases, they are not general-purpose and can only synthesize the combinations of words and phrases with which they have been preprogrammed.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The blending of words within naturally spoken language however can still cause problems unless the many variations are taken into account.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For example, in non-rhotic dialects of English the *"r"* in words like *"clear"* /ˈklɪə/ is usually only pronounced when the following word has a vowel as its first letter (e.g.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] *"clear out"* is realized as /ˌklɪəɹˈʌʊt/).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Likewise in French, many final consonants become no longer silent if followed by a word that begins with a vowel, an effect called liaison.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This alternation cannot be reproduced by a simple word-concatenation system, which would require additional complexity to be context-sensitive.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Formant synthesis does not use human speech samples at runtime.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Instead, the synthesized speech output is created using additive synthesis and an acoustic model (physical modelling synthesis).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Parameters such as fundamental frequency, voicing, and noise levels are varied over time to create a waveform of artificial speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This method is sometimes called *rules-based synthesis*; however, many concatenative systems also have rules-based components.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Many systems based on formant synthesis technology generate artificial, robotic-sounding speech that would never be mistaken for human speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, maximum naturalness is not always the goal of a speech synthesis system, and formant synthesis systems have advantages over concatenative systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Formant-synthesized speech can be reliably intelligible, even at very high speeds, avoiding the acoustic glitches that commonly plague concatenative systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] High-speed synthesized speech is used by the visually impaired to quickly navigate computers using a screen reader.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Formant synthesizers are usually smaller programs than concatenative systems because they do not have a database of speech samples.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] They can therefore be used in embedded systems, where memory and microprocessor power are especially limited.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Because formant-based systems have complete control of all aspects of the output speech, a wide variety of prosodies and intonations can be output, conveying not just questions and statements, but a variety of emotions and tones of voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Examples of non-real-time but highly accurate intonation control in formant synthesis include the work done in the late 1970s for the Texas Instruments toy Speak & Spell, and in the early 1980s Sega arcade machines and in many Atari, Inc. arcade games using the TMS5220 LPC Chips.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Creating proper intonation for these projects was painstaking, and the results have yet to be matched by real-time text-to-speech interfaces.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For tonal languages, such as Chinese or Taiwanese language, there are different levels of tone sandhi required and sometimes the output of speech synthesizer may result in the mistakes of tone sandhi.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Articulatory synthesis consists of computational techniques for synthesizing speech based on models of the human vocal tract and the articulation processes occurring there.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The first articulatory synthesizer regularly used for laboratory experiments was developed at Haskins Laboratories in the mid-1970s by Philip Rubin, Tom Baer, and Paul Mermelstein.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This synthesizer, known as ASY, was based on vocal tract models developed at Bell Laboratories in the 1960s and 1970s by Paul Mermelstein, Cecil Coker, and colleagues.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Until recently, articulatory synthesis models have not been incorporated into commercial speech synthesis systems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A notable exception is the NeXT-based system originally developed and marketed by Trillium Sound Research, a spin-off company of the University of Calgary, where much of the original research was conducted.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Following the demise of the various incarnations of NeXT (started by Steve Jobs in the late 1980s and merged with Apple Computer in 1997), the Trillium software was published under the GNU General Public License, with work continuing as gnuspeech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The system, first marketed in 1994, provides full articulatory-based text-to-speech conversion using a waveguide or transmission-line analog of the human oral and nasal tracts controlled by Carré's "distinctive region model".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] More recent synthesizers, developed by Jorge C.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Lucero and colleagues, incorporate models of vocal fold biomechanics, glottal aerodynamics and acoustic wave propagation in the bronchi, trachea, nasal and oral cavities, and thus constitute full systems of physics-based speech simulation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] HMM-based synthesis is a synthesis method based on hidden Markov models, also called Statistical Parametric Synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In this system, the frequency spectrum (vocal tract), fundamental frequency (voice source), and duration (prosody) of speech are modeled simultaneously by HMMs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech waveforms are generated from HMMs themselves based on the maximum likelihood criterion.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Sinewave synthesis is a technique for synthesizing speech by replacing the formants (main bands of energy) with pure tone whistles.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Deep learning speech synthesis uses deep neural networks (DNN) to produce artificial speech from text (text-to-speech) or spectrum (vocoder).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The deep neural networks are trained using a large amount of recorded speech and, in the case of a text-to-speech system, the associated labels and/or input text.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Audio deepfake technology, also referred to as voice cloning or deepfake audio, is an application of artificial intelligence designed to generate speech that convincingly mimics specific individuals, often synthesizing phrases or sentences they have never spoken.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Initially developed with the intent to enhance various aspects of human life, it has practical applications such as generating audiobooks and assisting individuals who have lost their voices due to medical conditions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Additionally, it has commercial uses, including the creation of personalized digital assistants, natural-sounding text-to-speech systems, and advanced speech translation services.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] As with other forms of deepfakes, audio deepfakes have faced criticism for their use in scams, phishing, and misinformation campaigns.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 2023, VICE reporter Joseph Cox published findings that he had recorded five minutes of himself talking and then used a tool developed by ElevenLabs to create voice deepfakes that defeated a bank's voice-authentication system.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The process of normalizing text is rarely straightforward.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Texts are full of heteronyms, numbers, and abbreviations that all require expansion into a phonetic representation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] There are many spellings in English which are pronounced differently based on context.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For example, "My latest project is to learn how to better project my voice" contains two pronunciations of "project".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Most text-to-speech (TTS) systems do not generate semantic representations of their input texts, as processes for doing so are unreliable, poorly understood, and computationally ineffective.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] As a result, various heuristic techniques are used to guess the proper way to disambiguate homographs, like examining neighboring words and using statistics about frequency of occurrence.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Recently TTS systems have begun to use HMMs (discussed above) to generate "parts of speech" to aid in disambiguating homographs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This technique is quite successful for many cases such as whether "read" should be pronounced as "red" implying past tense, or as "reed" implying present tense.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Typical error rates when using HMMs in this fashion are usually below five percent.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] These techniques also work well for most European languages, although access to required training corpora is frequently difficult in these languages.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Deciding how to convert numbers is another problem that TTS systems have to address.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It is a simple programming challenge to convert a number into words (at least in English), like "1325" becoming "one thousand three hundred twenty-five".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, numbers occur in many different contexts; "1325" may also be read as "one three two five", "thirteen twenty-five" or "thirteen hundred and twenty five".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A TTS system can often infer how to expand a number based on surrounding words, numbers, and punctuation, and sometimes the system provides a way to specify the context if it is ambiguous.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Roman numerals can also be read differently depending on context.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For example, "Henry VIII" reads as "Henry the Eighth", while "Chapter VIII" reads as "Chapter Eight".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Similarly, abbreviations can be ambiguous.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] For example, the abbreviation "in" for "inches" must be differentiated from the word "in", and the address "12 St John St." uses the same abbreviation for both "Saint" and "Street".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] TTS systems with intelligent front ends can make educated guesses about ambiguous abbreviations, while others provide the same result in all cases, resulting in nonsensical (and sometimes comical) outputs, such as "Ulysses S.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Grant" being rendered as "Ulysses South Grant".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems use two basic approaches to determine the pronunciation of a word based on its spelling, a process which is often called text-to-phoneme or grapheme-to-phoneme conversion (phoneme is the term used by linguists to describe distinctive sounds in a language).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The simplest approach to text-to-phoneme conversion is the dictionary-based approach, where a large dictionary containing all the words of a language and their correct pronunciations is stored by the program.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Determining the correct pronunciation of each word is a matter of looking up each word in the dictionary and replacing the spelling with the pronunciation specified in the dictionary.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The other approach is rule-based, in which pronunciation rules are applied to words to determine their pronunciations based on their spellings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This is similar to the "sounding out", or synthetic phonics, approach to learning reading.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Each approach has advantages and drawbacks.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The dictionary-based approach is quick and accurate, but completely fails if it is given a word which is not in its dictionary.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] As dictionary size grows, so too does the memory space requirements of the synthesis system.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, the rule-based approach works on any input, but the complexity of the rules grows substantially as the system takes into account irregular spellings or pronunciations.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] (Consider that the word "of" is very common in English, yet is the only word in which the letter "f" is pronounced [v].) As a result, nearly all speech synthesis systems use a combination of these approaches.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Languages with a phonemic orthography have a very regular writing system, and the prediction of the pronunciation of words based on their spellings is quite successful.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems for such languages often use the rule-based method extensively, resorting to dictionaries only for those few words, like foreign names and loanwords, whose pronunciations are not obvious from their spellings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, speech synthesis systems for languages like English, which have extremely irregular spelling systems, are more likely to rely on dictionaries, and to use rule-based methods only for unusual words, or words that are not in their dictionaries.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The consistent evaluation of speech synthesis systems may be difficult because of a lack of universally agreed objective evaluation criteria.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Different organizations often use different speech data.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The quality of speech synthesis systems also depends on the quality of the production technique (which may involve analogue or digital recording) and on the facilities used to replay the speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Evaluating speech synthesis systems has therefore often been compromised by differences between production techniques and replay facilities.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Since 2005, however, some researchers have started to evaluate speech synthesis systems using a common speech dataset.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A study in the journal *Speech Communication* by Amy Drahota and colleagues at the University of Portsmouth, UK, reported that listeners to voice recordings could determine, at better than chance levels, whether or not the speaker was smiling.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It was suggested that identification of the vocal features that signal emotional content may be used to help make synthesized speech sound more natural.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] One of the related issues is modification of the pitch contour of the sentence, depending upon whether it is an affirmative, interrogative or exclamatory sentence.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] One of the techniques for pitch modification uses discrete cosine transform in the source domain (linear prediction residual).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Such pitch synchronous pitch modification techniques need a priori pitch marking of the synthesis speech database using techniques such as epoch extraction using dynamic plosion index applied on the integrated linear prediction residual of the voiced regions of speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In general, prosody remains a challenge for speech synthesizers, and is an active research topic.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Popular systems offering speech synthesis as a built-in capability.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In the early 1980s, TI was known as a pioneer in speech synthesis, and a highly popular plug-in speech synthesizer module was available for the TI-99/4 and 4A.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesizers were offered free with the purchase of a number of cartridges and were used by many TI-written video games (games offered with speech during this promotion included *Alpiner* and *Parsec*).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The synthesizer uses a variant of linear predictive coding and has a small in-built vocabulary.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The original intent was to release small cartridges that plugged directly into the synthesizer unit, which would increase the device's built-in vocabulary.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] However, the success of software text-to-speech in the Terminal Emulator II cartridge canceled that plan.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Mattel Intellivision game console offered the Intellivoice Voice Synthesis module in 1982.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It included the SP0256 Narrator speech synthesizer chip on a removable cartridge.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Narrator had 2kB of Read-Only Memory (ROM), and this was utilized to store a database of generic words that could be combined to make phrases in Intellivision games.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Since the Orator chip could also accept speech data from external memory, any additional words or phrases needed could be stored inside the cartridge itself.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The data consisted of strings of analog-filter coefficients to modify the behavior of the chip's synthetic vocal-tract model, rather than simple digitized samples.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Also released in 1982, Software Automatic Mouth was the first commercial all-software voice synthesis program.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It was later used as the basis for Macintalk.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The program was available for non-Macintosh Apple computers (including the Apple II, and the Lisa), various Atari models and the Commodore 64.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Apple version preferred additional hardware that contained DACs, although it could instead use the computer's one-bit audio output (with the addition of much distortion) if the card was not present.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Atari made use of the embedded POKEY audio chip.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech playback on the Atari normally disabled interrupt requests and shut down the ANTIC chip during vocal output.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The audible output is extremely distorted speech when the screen is on.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Commodore 64 made use of the 64's embedded SID audio chip.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Arguably, the first speech system integrated into an operating system was the circa 1983 unreleased Atari 1400XL/1450XL computers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] These used the Votrax SC01 chip and a finite-state machine to enable World English Spelling text-to-speech synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The Atari ST computers were sold with "stspeech.tos" on floppy disk.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The first speech system integrated into an operating system that shipped in quantity was Apple Computer's MacInTalk.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The software was licensed from third-party developers Joseph Katz and Mark Barton (later, SoftVoice, Inc.) and was featured during the 1984 introduction of the Macintosh computer.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This January demo required 512 kilobytes of RAM.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] As a result, it could not run in the 128 kilobytes of RAM the first Mac actually shipped with.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] So, the demo was accomplished with a prototype 512k Mac, although those in attendance were not told of this and the synthesis demo created considerable excitement for the Macintosh.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In the early 1990s Apple expanded its capabilities offering system wide text-to-speech support.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] With the introduction of faster PowerPC-based computers they included higher quality voice sampling.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Apple also introduced speech recognition into its systems which provided a fluid command set.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] More recently, Apple has added sample-based voices.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Starting as a curiosity, the speech system of Apple Macintosh has evolved into a fully supported program, PlainTalk, for people with vision problems.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] VoiceOver was for the first time featured in 2005 in Mac OS X Tiger (10.4).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] During 10.4 (Tiger) and first releases of 10.5 (Leopard) there was only one standard voice shipping with Mac OS X.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Starting with 10.6 (Snow Leopard), the user can choose out of a wide range list of multiple voices.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] VoiceOver voices feature the taking of realistic-sounding breaths between sentences, as well as improved clarity at high read rates over PlainTalk.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Mac OS X also includes say, a command-line based application that converts text to audible speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The AppleScript Standard Additions includes a say verb that allows a script to use any of the installed voices and to control the pitch, speaking rate and modulation of the spoken text.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Used in Alexa and as Software as a Service in AWS (from 2017).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The second operating system to feature advanced speech synthesis capabilities was AmigaOS, introduced in 1985.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The voice synthesis was licensed by Commodore International from SoftVoice, Inc., who also developed the original MacinTalk text-to-speech system.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It featured a complete system of voice emulation for American English, with both male and female voices and "stress" indicator markers, made possible through the Amiga's audio chipset.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The synthesis system was divided into a translator library which converted unrestricted English text into a standard set of phonetic codes and a narrator device which implemented a formant model of speech generation..
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] AmigaOS also featured a high-level "Speak Handler", which allowed command-line users to redirect text output to speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis was occasionally used in third-party programs, particularly word processors and educational software.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The synthesis software remained largely unchanged from the first AmigaOS release and Commodore eventually removed speech synthesis support from AmigaOS 2.1 onward.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Despite the American English phoneme limitation, an unofficial version with multilingual speech synthesis was developed.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] This made use of an enhanced version of the translator library which could translate a number of languages, given a set of rules for each language.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Modern Windows desktop systems can use SAPI 4 and SAPI 5 components to support speech synthesis and speech recognition.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] SAPI 4.0 was available as an optional add-on for Windows 95 and Windows 98.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Windows 2000 added Narrator, a text-to-speech utility for people who have visual impairment.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Third-party programs such as JAWS for Windows, Window-Eyes, Non-visual Desktop Access, Supernova and System Access can perform various text-to-speech tasks such as reading text aloud from a specified website, email account, text document, the Windows clipboard, the user's keyboard typing, etc.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Not all programs can use speech synthesis directly.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Some programs can use plug-ins, extensions or add-ons to read text aloud.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Third-party programs are available that can read text from the system clipboard.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Microsoft Speech Server is a server-based package for voice synthesis and recognition.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It is designed for network use with web applications and call centers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] From 1971 to 1996, Votrax produced a number of commercial speech synthesizer components.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A Votrax synthesizer was included in the first generation Kurzweil Reading Machine for the Blind.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech (TTS) refers to the ability of computers to read text aloud.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A TTS engine converts written text to a phonemic representation, then converts the phonemic representation to waveforms that can be output as sound.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] TTS engines with different languages, dialects and specialized vocabularies are available through third-party publishers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Version 1.6 of Android added support for speech synthesis (TTS).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Currently, there are a number of applications, plugins and gadgets that can read messages directly from an e-mail client and web pages from a web browser or Google Toolbar.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Some specialized software can narrate RSS-feeds.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] On one hand, online RSS-narrators simplify information delivery by allowing users to listen to their favourite news sources and to convert them to podcasts.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, on-line RSS-readers are available on almost any personal computer connected to the Internet.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Users can download generated audio files to portable devices, e.g. with a help of podcast receiver, and listen to them while walking, jogging or commuting to work.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A growing field in Internet based TTS is web-based assistive technology, e.g.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] 'Browsealoud' from a UK company and Readspeaker.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It can deliver TTS functionality to anyone (for reasons of accessibility, convenience, entertainment or information) with access to a web browser.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The non-profit project Pediaphon was created in 2006 to provide a similar web-based TTS interface to the Wikipedia.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Other work is being done in the context of the W3C through the W3C Audio Incubator Group with the involvement of The BBC and Google Inc.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Also researchers from Baidu Research presented a voice cloning system with similar aims at the 2018 NeurIPS conference, though the result is rather unconvincing.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] By 2019 the digital sound-alikes found their way to the hands of criminals as Symantec researchers know of 3 cases where digital sound-alikes technology has been used for crime.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A number of markup languages have been established for the rendition of text as speech in an XML-compliant format.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The most recent is Speech Synthesis Markup Language (SSML), which became a W3C recommendation in 2004.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Older speech synthesis markup languages include Java Speech Markup Language (JSML) and SABLE.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Although each of these was proposed as a standard, none of them have been widely adopted.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis markup languages are distinguished from dialogue markup languages.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] VoiceXML, for example, includes tags related to speech recognition, dialogue management and touchtone dialing, in addition to text-to-speech markup.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis has long been a vital assistive technology tool and its application in this area is significant and widespread.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] It allows environmental barriers to be removed for people with a wide range of disabilities.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The longest application has been in the use of screen readers for people with visual impairment, but text-to-speech systems are now commonly used by people with dyslexia and other reading disabilities as well as by pre-literate children.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] They are also frequently employed to aid those with severe speech impairment usually through a dedicated voice output communication aid.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Work to personalize a synthetic voice to better match a person's personality or historical voice is becoming available.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A noted application, of speech synthesis, was the Kurzweil Reading Machine for the Blind which incorporated text-to-phonetics software based on work from Haskins Laboratories and a black-box synthesizer built by Votrax.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis techniques are also used in entertainment productions such as games and animations.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In 2007, Animo Limited announced the development of a software application package based on its speech synthesis software FineSpeech, explicitly geared towards customers in the entertainment industries, able to generate narration and lines of dialogue according to user specifications.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The application reached maturity in 2008, when NEC Biglobe announced a web service that allows users to create phrases from the voices of characters from the Japanese anime series *Code Geass: Lelouch of the Rebellion R2*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] 15.ai has been frequently used for content creation in various fandoms, including the *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic* fandom, the *Team Fortress 2* fandom, the *Portal* fandom, and the *SpongeBob SquarePants* fandom.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech for disability and impaired communication aids have become widely available.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech is also finding new applications; for example, speech synthesis combined with speech recognition allows for interaction with mobile devices via natural language processing interfaces.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Some users have also created AI virtual assistants using 15.ai and external voice control software.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech is also used in second language acquisition.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Voki, for instance, is an educational tool created by Oddcast that allows users to create their own talking avatar, using different accents.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] They can be emailed, embedded on websites or shared on social media.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Content creators have used voice cloning tools to recreate their voices for podcasts, narration, and comedy shows.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Publishers and authors have also used such software to narrate audiobooks and newsletters.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Another area of application is AI video creation with talking heads.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Webapps and video editors like Elai.io or Synthesia allow users to create video content involving AI avatars, who are made to speak using text-to-speech technology.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis is a valuable computational aid for the analysis and assessment of speech disorders.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] A voice quality synthesizer, developed by Jorge C.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Lucero et al. at the University of Brasília, simulates the physics of phonation and includes models of vocal frequency jitter and tremor, airflow noise and laryngeal asymmetries.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] The synthesizer has been used to mimic the timbre of dysphonic speakers with controlled levels of roughness, breathiness and strain.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] In the 2010s, singing synthesis technology took advantage of the advances in artificial intelligence, deep listening and machine learning, to better represent the nuances of the human voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] New high-fidelity sample libraries combined with digital audio workstations facilitate editing in fine detail, such as shifting of formants, adjustment of vibrato, and adjustments to vowels and consonants.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] Sample libraries for various languages and various accents are available.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/speech-synthesis] With advancements in vocal synthesis, artists sometimes use sample libraries in lieu of backing singers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] A **vocoder** (/ˈvoʊkoʊdər/, a portmanteau of *vo*ice and en*coder*) is a category of speech coding that analyzes and synthesizes the human voice signal for audio data compression, multiplexing, voice encryption or voice transformation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The vocoder was invented in 1937 by Homer Dudley at Bell Labs as a means of synthesizing human speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This work was developed into the **channel vocoder** which was used as a voice codec for telecommunications for speech coding to conserve bandwidth in transmission.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] By encrypting the control signals, voice transmission can be secured against interception.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Its primary use in this fashion is for secure radio communication.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The advantage of this method of encryption is that none of the original signal is sent, only envelopes of the bandpass filters.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The receiving unit needs to be set up in the same filter configuration to re-synthesize a version of the original signal spectrum.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The vocoder has also been used extensively as an electronic musical instrument.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The decoder portion of the vocoder, called a voder, can be used independently for speech synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The human voice consists of sounds generated by the periodic opening and closing of the glottis by the vocal cords, which produces an acoustic waveform with many harmonics.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This initial sound is then filtered by movements in the nose, mouth and throat (a complicated resonant piping system known as the vocal tract) to produce fluctuations in harmonic content (formants) in a controlled way, creating the wide variety of sounds used in speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] There is another set of sounds, known as the unvoiced and plosive sounds, which are created or modified by a variety of sound-generating disruptions of airflow occurring in the vocal tract.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The vocoder analyzes speech by measuring how its spectral energy distribution characteristics fluctuate across time.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This analysis results in a set of temporally parallel envelope signals, each representing the individual frequency band amplitudes of the user's speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This set of envelope amplitude signals is called the "modulator".
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The digital encoding process involves a periodic analysis of each of the modulator's multiband set of envelope amplitudes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This analysis results in a set of digital pulse code modulation stream readings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Then the pulse code modulation stream outputs of each band are transmitted to a decoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The decoder applies the pulse code modulations as control signals to the corresponding amplifiers of the output filter channels.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Information about the fundamental frequency of the initial voice signal (as distinct from its spectral characteristic) is discarded; it was not important to preserve this for the vocoder's original use as an encryption aid.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] It is this dehumanizing aspect of the vocoding process that has made it useful in creating special voice effects in popular music and audio entertainment.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Instead of a point-by-point recreation of the waveform, the vocoder process sends only the parameters of the vocal model over the communication link.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Since the parameters change slowly compared to the original speech waveform, the bandwidth required to transmit speech can be reduced.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This allows more speech channels to utilize a given communication channel, such as a radio channel or a submarine cable.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Analog vocoders typically analyze an incoming signal by splitting the signal into multiple tuned frequency bands or ranges.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] To reconstruct the signal, a carrier signal is sent through a series of these tuned band-pass filters.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In the example of a typical robot voice the carrier is noise or a sawtooth waveform.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] There are usually between 8 and 20 bands.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The amplitude of the modulator for each of the individual analysis bands generates a voltage that is used to control amplifiers for each of the corresponding carrier bands.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The result is that frequency components of the modulating signal are mapped onto the carrier signal as discrete amplitude changes in each of the frequency bands.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Often there is an unvoiced band or sibilance channel.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This is for frequencies that are outside the analysis bands for typical speech but are still important in speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Examples are words that start with the letters *s*, *f*, *ch* or any other sibilant sound.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Using this band produces recognizable speech, although somewhat mechanical sounding.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Vocoders often include a second system for generating unvoiced sounds, using a noise generator instead of the fundamental frequency.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This is mixed with the carrier output to increase clarity.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In the channel vocoder algorithm, among the two components of an analytic signal, considering only the amplitude component and simply ignoring the phase component tends to result in an unclear voice; on methods for rectifying this, see phase vocoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The development of a vocoder was started in 1928 by Bell Labs engineer Homer Dudley, who was granted patents for it on March 21, 1939, and Nov 16, 1937.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] To demonstrate the speech synthesis ability of its decoder section, the voder (voice operating demonstrator) was introduced to the public at the AT&T building at the 1939–1940 New York World's Fair.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The filters controlled by keys convert the tone and the hiss into vowels, consonants, and inflections.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This was a complex machine to operate, but a skilled operator could produce recognizable speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Dudley's vocoder was used in the SIGSALY system, which was built by Bell Labs engineers in 1943.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] SIGSALY was used for encrypted voice communications during World War II.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The KO-6 voice coder was released in 1949 in limited quantities; it was a close approximation to the SIGSALY at 1200 bit/s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Later work in this field has since used digital speech coding.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The most widely used speech coding technique is linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Another speech coding technique, adaptive differential pulse-code modulation (ADPCM), was developed by P.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Even with the need to record several frequencies and additional unvoiced sounds, the compression of vocoder systems is impressive.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Standard speech-recording systems capture frequencies from about 500 to 3,400 Hz, where most of the frequencies used in speech lie, typically using a sampling rate of 8 kHz (slightly greater than the Nyquist rate).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The sampling resolution is typically 8 or more bits per sample, for a data rate in the range of 64 kbit/s, but a good vocoder can provide a reasonably good simulation of voice with as little as 5 kbit/s of data.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Vocoders are also currently used in psychophysics, linguistics, computational neuroscience and cochlear implant research.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Since the late 1970s, most non-musical vocoders have been implemented using linear prediction, whereby the target signal's spectral envelope (formant) is estimated by an all-pole IIR filter.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In linear prediction coding, the all-pole filter replaces the bandpass filter bank of its predecessor and is used at the encoder to *whiten* the signal (i.e., flatten the spectrum) and again at the decoder to re-apply the spectral shape of the target speech signal.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] One advantage of this type of filtering is that the location of the linear predictor's spectral peaks is entirely determined by the target signal and can be as precise as allowed by the time period to be filtered.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This is in contrast with vocoders realized using fixed-width filter banks, where the location of spectral peaks is constrained by the available fixed frequency bands.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] LP filtering also has disadvantages in that signals with a large number of constituent frequencies may exceed the number of frequencies that can be represented by the linear prediction filter.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] This restriction is the primary reason that LP coding is almost always used in tandem with other methods in high-compression voice coders.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Waveform-interpolative (WI) vocoder was developed at AT&T Bell Laboratories around 1995 by W.B.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Kleijn, and subsequently, a low-complexity version was developed by AT&T for the DoD secure vocoder competition.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Notable enhancements to the WI coder were made at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] AT&T holds the core patents related to WI and other institutes hold additional patents.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] For musical applications, a source of musical sounds is used as the carrier, instead of extracting the fundamental frequency.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] For instance, one could use the sound of a synthesizer as the input to the filter bank, a technique that became popular in the 1970s.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Werner Meyer-Eppler, a German scientist with a special interest in electronic voice synthesis, published a thesis in 1948 on electronic music and speech synthesis from the viewpoint of sound synthesis.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Later he was instrumental in the founding of the Studio for Electronic Music of WDR in Cologne, in 1951.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] One of the first attempts to use a vocoder in creating music was the *Siemens Synthesizer* at the Siemens Studio for Electronic Music, developed between 1956 and 1959.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In 1968, Robert Moog developed one of the first solid-state musical vocoders for the electronic music studio of the University at Buffalo.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In 1968, Bruce Haack built a prototype vocoder, named *Farad* after Michael Faraday.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] It was first featured on "The Electronic Record For Children" released in 1969 and then on his rock album *The Electric Lucifer* released in 1970.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Vocoder effects have been used by musicians in both electronic music and as a special effect, along with more traditional instruments.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In 1969, Sly and the Family Stone used it in "Sex Machine", a song on the album *Stand!*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Other artists have made vocoders an essential part of their music, overall or during an extended phase.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Examples include the German synthpop group Kraftwerk, US funk band Midnight Star ("Freak-A-Zoid"), Stevie Wonder ("Send One Your Love", "A Seed's a Star") and jazz/fusion keyboardist Herbie Hancock during his late 1970s period.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] In 1982 Neil Young used a Sennheiser Vocoder VSM201 on six of the nine tracks on *Trans*.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The chorus and bridge of Michael Jackson's "P.Y.T.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] (Pretty Young Thing)" features a vocoder ("Pretty young thing/You make me sing"), courtesy of session musician Michael Boddicker.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] For instance, the lyrics of "Around the World" (1997) are integrally vocoder-processed, "Get Lucky" (2013) features a mix of natural and processed human voices, and "Instant Crush" (2013) features Julian Casablancas singing into a vocoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Robot voices became a recurring element in popular music during the 20th century.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Apart from vocoders, several other methods of producing variations on this effect include: the Sonovox, Talk box, Auto-Tune, linear prediction vocoders, speech synthesis, ring modulation and comb filter.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] Vocoders are used in television production, filmmaking and games, usually for robots or talking computers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The robot voices of the Cylons in *Battlestar Galactica* were created with an EMS Vocoder 2000.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] The 1980 version of the *Doctor Who* theme, as arranged and recorded by Peter Howell, has a section of the main melody generated by a Roland SVC-350 vocoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/vocoder] A similar Roland VP-330 vocoder was used to create the voice of Soundwave, a character from the *Transformers* series.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Replay-based deepfakes are malicious works that aim to reproduce a recording of the interlocutor's voice.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] There are two types: *far-field* detection and *cut-and-paste* detection.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In far-field detection, a microphone recording of the victim is played as a test segment on a hands-free phone.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] On the other hand, cut-and-paste involves faking the requested sentence from a text-dependent system.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Text-dependent speaker verification can be used to defend against replay-based attacks.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] A current technique that detects end-to-end replay attacks is the use of deep convolutional neural networks.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The category based on speech synthesis refers to the artificial production of human speech, using software or hardware system programs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Speech synthesis includes text-to-speech, which aims to transform the text into acceptable and natural speech in real-time, making the speech sound in line with the text input, using the rules of linguistic description of the text.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] A classical system of this type consists of three modules: a text analysis model, an acoustic model, and a vocoder.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The generation usually has to follow two essential steps.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] It is necessary to collect clean and well-structured raw audio with the transcribed text of the original speech audio sentence.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Second, the text-to-speech model must be trained using these data to build a synthetic audio generation model.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Specifically, the transcribed text with the target speaker's voice is the input of the generation model.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The text analysis module processes the input text and converts it into linguistic features.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Then, the acoustic module extracts the parameters of the target speaker from the audio data based on the linguistic features generated by the text analysis module.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Finally, the vocoder learns to create vocal waveforms based on the parameters of the acoustic features.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The final audio file is generated, including the synthetic simulation audio in a waveform format, creating speech audio in the voice of many speakers, even those not in training.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The first breakthrough in this regard was introduced by WaveNet, a neural network for generating raw audio waveforms capable of emulating the characteristics of many different speakers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This network has been overtaken over the years by other systems which synthesize highly realistic artificial voices within everyone's reach.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Text-to-speech is highly dependent on the quality of the voice corpus used to realize the system, and creating an entire voice corpus is expensive.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Another disadvantage is that speech synthesis systems do not recognize periods or special characters.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Also, ambiguity problems are persistent, as two words written in the same way can have different meanings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Audio deepfake based on imitation is a way of transforming an original speech from one speaker - the original - so that it sounds spoken like another speaker - the target one.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] An imitation-based algorithm takes a spoken signal as input and alters it by changing its style, intonation, or prosody, trying to mimic the target voice without changing the linguistic information.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This technique is also known as voice conversion.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This method is often confused with the previous synthetic-based method, as there is no clear separation between the two approaches regarding the generation process.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Indeed, both methods modify acoustic-spectral and style characteristics of the speech audio signal, but the Imitation-based usually keeps the input and output text unaltered.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This is obtained by changing how this sentence is spoken to match the target speaker's characteristics.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Voices can be imitated in several ways, such as using humans with similar voices that can mimic the original speaker.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In recent years, the most popular approach involves the use of particular neural networks called generative adversarial networks (GAN) due to their flexibility as well as high-quality results.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Then, the original audio signal is transformed to say a speech in the target audio using an imitation generation method that generates a new speech, shown in the fake one.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The audio deepfake detection task determines whether the given speech audio is real or fake.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Recently, this has become a hot topic in the forensic research community, trying to keep up with the rapid evolution of counterfeiting techniques.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In general, deepfake detection methods can be divided into two categories based on the aspect they leverage to perform the detection task.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The first focuses on low-level aspects, looking for artifacts introduced by the generators at the sample level.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The second, instead, focus on higher-level features representing more complex aspects as the semantic content of the speech audio recording.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Many machine learning models have been developed using different strategies to detect fake audio.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The output is fed into the final module to produce a prediction probability of the *Fake* class or the *Real* one.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Over the years, many researchers have shown that machine learning approaches are more accurate than deep learning methods, regardless of the features used.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] However, the scalability of machine learning methods is not confirmed due to excessive training and manual feature extraction, especially with many audio files.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Instead, when deep learning algorithms are used, specific transformations are required on the audio files to ensure that the algorithms can handle them.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Most detection studies focus on English language deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Research on the most spoken languages like Chinese and Spanish remains limited.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Detection models trained primarily on English show reduced performance when tested on non-English audio.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Accent variation also affects detection accuracy.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Different pronunciations associated with specific regions or populations influence how well models identify synthetic speech.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] There are several open-source implementations of different detection methods, and usually many research groups release them on a public hosting service like GitHub.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The increasing accessibility of audio deepfake technology has faced concerns over their use in scams and misinformation campaigns.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] People can use them as a logical access voice spoofing technique, where they can be used to manipulate public opinion for propaganda, defamation, or terrorism.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Vast amounts of voice recordings are daily transmitted over the Internet, and spoofing detection is challenging.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Audio deepfake attackers have targeted individuals and organizations, including politicians and governments.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In 2019, scammers using AI impersonated the voice of the CEO of a German energy company and directed the CEO of its UK subsidiary to transfer €220,000.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In early 2020, the same technique impersonated a company director as part of an elaborate scheme that convinced a branch manager to transfer $35 million.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] According to a 2023 global McAfee survey, one person in ten reported having been targeted by an AI voice cloning scam; 77% of these targets reported losing money to the scam.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Audio deepfakes could also pose a danger to voice ID systems currently used by financial institutions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In March 2023, the United States Federal Trade Commission issued a warning to consumers about the use of AI to fake the voice of a family member in distress asking for money.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In October 2023, during the start of the British Labour Party's conference in Liverpool, an audio deepfake of Labour leader Keir Starmer was released that falsely portrayed him verbally abusing his staffers and criticizing Liverpool.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] That same month, an audio deepfake of Slovak politician Michal Šimečka falsely claimed to capture him discussing ways to rig the upcoming election.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] During the campaign for the 2024 New Hampshire Democratic presidential primary, over 20,000 voters received robocalls from an AI-impersonated President Joe Biden urging them not to vote.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The New Hampshire attorney general said this violated state election laws, and alleged involvement by Life Corporation and Lingo Telecom.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In February 2024, the United States Federal Communications Commission banned the use of AI to fake voices in robocalls.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] That same month, political consultant Steve Kramer admitted that he had commissioned the calls for $500.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] He said that he wanted to call attention to the need for rules governing the use of AI in political campaigns.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In May, the FCC said that Kramer had violated federal law by spoofing the number of a local political figure, and proposed a fine of $6 million.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Four New Hampshire counties indicted Kramer on felony counts of voter suppression, and impersonating a candidate, a misdemeanor.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In 2024, YouTuber Jeff Geerling received attention after noticing his voice was cloned without consent by the electronics manufacturer Elecrow, and the company subsequently apologized and removed the offending content.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Geerling's experience was cited as a case meant to be addressed by YouTube's likeness-detection technology when it was released in 2025.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In February 2023, research firm Graphika documented the first known case of state-aligned actors using AI-generated news anchors for political disinformation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The Chinese propaganda network Spamouflage created two fictitious news presenters named "Alex" and "Anna" using Synthesia AI software.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The deepfake anchors appeared in videos posted to Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube starting in late 2022.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Videos promoted pro-China narratives and criticized the United States.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The operation cost approximately $30 per month for the AI software subscription.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Detection indicators included robotic speech patterns, lip-sync errors, and grammatical mistakes in video subtitles.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The audio deepfake is a very recent field of research.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] For this reason, there are many possibilities for development and improvement, as well as possible threats that adopting this technology can bring to our daily lives.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The most important ones are listed below.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] A 2023 comprehensive survey on audio deepfake detection found that detection systems face significant challenges in generalizing across different generation methods and acoustic conditions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Regarding the generation, the most significant aspect is the credibility of the victim, i.e., the perceptual quality of the audio deepfake.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Several metrics determine the level of accuracy of audio deepfake generation, and the most widely used is the mean opinion score (MOS), which is the arithmetic average of user ratings.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Usually, the test to be rated involves perceptual evaluation of sentences made by different speech generation algorithms.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This index showed that audio generated by algorithms trained on a single speaker has a higher MOS.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The sampling rate also plays an essential role in detecting and generating audio deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Currently, available datasets have a sampling rate of around 16 kHz, significantly reducing speech quality.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] An increase in the sampling rate could lead to higher quality generation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In March 2020, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology researcher demonstrated data-efficient audio deepfake generation through 15.ai, a web application capable of generating high-quality speech using only 15 seconds of training data, compared to previous systems that required tens of hours.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The system implemented a unified multi-speaker model that enabled simultaneous training of multiple voices through speaker embeddings, allowing the model to learn shared patterns across different voices even when individual voices lacked examples of certain emotional contexts.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The platform integrated sentiment analysis through DeepMoji for emotional expression and supported precise pronunciation control via ARPABET phonetic transcriptions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The 15-second data efficiency benchmark was later corroborated by OpenAI in 2024.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Focusing on the detection part, one principal weakness affecting recent models is the adopted language.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Most studies focus on detecting audio deepfake in the English language, not paying much attention to the most spoken languages like Chinese and Spanish, as well as Hindi and Arabic.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] It is also essential to consider more factors related to different accents that represent the way of pronunciation strictly associated with a particular individual, location, or nation.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In other fields of audio, such as speaker recognition, the accent has been found to influence the performance significantly, so it is expected that this feature could affect the models' performance even in this detection task.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In addition, the excessive preprocessing of the audio data has led to a very high and often unsustainable computational cost.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] For this reason, many researchers have suggested following a self-supervised learning approach, dealing with unlabeled data to work effectively in detection tasks and improving the model's scalability, and, at the same time, decreasing the computational cost.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Moreover, a key factor in handling unknown spoofing attacks lies in the use of effective data augmentation strategies, which expose the model to a broader range of acoustic variability and enhance its ability to generalize to unseen attack conditions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Training and testing models with real audio data is still an underdeveloped area.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Indeed, using audio with real-world background noises can increase the robustness of the fake audio detection models.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In addition, most of the effort is focused on detecting synthetic-based audio deepfakes, and few studies are analyzing imitation-based due to their intrinsic difficulty in the generation process.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Over the years, there has been an increase in techniques aimed at defending against malicious actions that audio deepfake could bring, such as identity theft and manipulation of speeches by the nation's governors.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] To prevent deepfakes, some suggest using blockchain and other distributed ledger technologies (DLT) to identify the provenance of data and track information.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Extracting and comparing affective cues corresponding to perceived emotions from digital content has also been proposed to combat deepfakes.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Another critical aspect concerns the mitigation of this problem.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] It has been suggested that it would be better to keep some proprietary detection tools only for those who need them, such as fact-checkers for journalists.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] That way, those who create the generation models, perhaps for nefarious purposes, would not know precisely what features facilitate the detection of a deepfake, discouraging possible attackers.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] To improve the detection instead, researchers are trying to generalize the process, looking for preprocessing techniques that improve performance and testing different loss functions used for training.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In January 2023, China implemented regulations requiring deepfake content to be clearly labeled.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The rules prohibit using deep synthesis technology to produce or disseminate fake news.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Service providers must verify user identities and maintain content logs.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The regulations represent one of the first comprehensive government frameworks specifically targeting deepfake technology.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Numerous research groups worldwide are working to recognize media manipulations; i.e., audio deepfakes but also image and video deepfake.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] These projects are usually supported by public or private funding and are in close contact with universities and research institutions.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] For this purpose, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) runs the Semantic Forensics (SemaFor).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Another research program is the Preserving Media Trustworthiness in the Artificial Intelligence Era (PREMIER) program, funded by the Italian Ministry of Education, University and Research (MIUR) and run by five Italian universities.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] PREMIER will pursue novel hybrid approaches to obtain forensic detectors that are more interpretable and secure.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] DEEP-VOICE is a publicly available dataset intended for research purposes to develop systems to detect when speech has been generated with neural networks through a process called Retrieval-based Voice Conversion (RVC).
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Preliminary research showed numerous statistically significant differences between features found in human speech and that which had been generated by Artificial Intelligence algorithms.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] In the last few years, numerous challenges have been organized to push this field of audio deepfake research even further.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] The most famous world challenge is the ASVspoof, the Automatic Speaker Verification Spoofing and Countermeasures Challenge.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This challenge is a bi-annual community-led initiative that aims to promote the consideration of spoofing and the development of countermeasures.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Another recent challenge is the ADD—Audio Deepfake Detection—which considers fake situations in a more real-life scenario.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] Also the Voice Conversion Challenge is a bi-annual challenge, created with the need to compare different voice conversion systems and approaches using the same voice data.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] This replaced older messages recorded by Fletcher Mathers without her permission.
[src:voice-cloning-ml/voice-cloning] On 25 August 2025, ScotRail announced that they will replace the AI voice on trains, however it's not confirmed if this will be a human recording or another AI-trained voice.
